{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2015}} {{Use Australian English|date=June 2015}} {{Infobox video game |title = AFL |image = AFLWiiCover.jpg |caption = Game cover |developer = [[Wicked Witch Software]] |publisher = [[Tru Blu Entertainment]] |series = ''[[AFL (video game series)|AFL]]'' |released = {{vgrelease|AUS|19 May 2011<ref name=TruBlu>{{cite web|url=http://www.trublu.com.au/newsite/products/resultsdetailed.php?search=aflwii|title=Tru Blu release date|last=|first=|date=|work=|publisher=Tru Blu|accessdate=15 April 2011}}</ref>}} ''Game of the Year Edition'' {{vgrelease|AUS|12 July 2012}} |genre = [[Sports game|Sports]] |modes = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]], [[Multiplayer video game|multiplayer]] |platforms = [[Wii]] }}
'''''AFL''''' (usually referred to as '''''AFL Wii''''') is an [[AFL (video game series)|AFL]] [[sports game]] for the [[Nintendo Wii|Wii]]. It was developed by [[Wicked Witch Software]].<ref name=AussieNintendo>{{cite web|url=http://www.aussie-nintendo.com/news/25444|title=First Nintendo Wii Screens|last=|first=|date=|work=|publisher=Aussie Nintendo|accessdate=6 April 2011}}</ref> It was released on 19 May 2011.<ref name="TruBlu"/> Commentating is provided by [[Dennis Cometti]] and [[Brian Taylor (Australian footballer)|Brian Taylor]].<ref name=" MMGN.com ">{{cite web | url = http://wii.mmgn.com/News/AFL-Live-2011-Wii-Screens | title = AFL 2011 Wii |last=|first=|date=|work=|publisher=MMGM| accessdate = 2011-04-07}}</ref>
== Game features == *16 stadiums *5 different leagues (AFL, VFL, TAC Cup, NAB U18's National Championships, International Cup). *Over 70 licensed teams *Arcade style gameplay *29 player attributes *10 year career management mode.<ref name="HES AFL Wii">{{cite web|url=http://www.trublu.com.au/newsite/products/resultsdetailed.php?search=aflwii |title=Tru Blu AFL Wii Overview|last=|first=|date=|work=|publisher=Tru Blu|accessdate=12 April 2011}}</ref> *5 mini games.<ref name=Tsumea>{{cite web|url=http://www.tsumea.com/games-developer/wicked-witch/game/afl-wii |title=Tsumea AFL Wii|last=|first=|date=|work=|publisher=Tsumea|accessdate=6 April 2011}}</ref>
== Gameplay == Team management appears to focus on coaching, training, trading, drafting, tribunal and budget, while the in game gameplay, covers the actual game of the sport itself. The game has more arcade elements then the [[Big Ant Studios]] [[AFL Live|version]], but claims to still maintain a fair amount of simulation and options to set the level of this. On screen meters can also be turned on and off.
The game supports 3 controller types; The standard Wii remote, the Wii remote with the Nunchuck and the Game Cube Controller. Wicked Witch stated that the controls are intuitive but can take time to learn. Wii remote shaking is used to successfully tackle or break a tackle. There are 4 types of kicks including Drop Punts, Torpedoes, Snaps (Check Sides) and Grubbers but only 1 type of handball which increases in elevation depending on power.
The game also features a ten-year manager mode.
=== Multiplayer === Multiplayer supports up to 8 players<ref name=IGN>{{cite web|url=http://au.wii.ign.com/objects/105/105573.html|title=AFL Wii IGN |last=|first=|date=|work=|publisher=IGN|accessdate=12 April 2011}}</ref> but does not include online gameplay. Players can drop in and out of a career game.
==Game of the Year Edition== The Game of the Year Edition was released on 12 July 2012 for the Wii. It is an update for the [[2012 AFL season]], with updated team lists and on-field uniforms for the 2012 season, [[Sydney Showground Stadium|Skoda Stadium]] is to be playable and the ability to play as the [[Greater Western Sydney Giants]].<ref name=TruBlu2>{{cite web|url=http://www.trublu.com.au/newsite/infopages.php?pagerequest=aflgoty|title=Game of the Year Edition release date|last=|first=|date=|work=|publisher=Tru Blu Entertainment|accessdate=1 June 2011}}</ref>
